07497nam a22010335i 9780812205695DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20112001pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1004872505  a97808122056957 a10.9783/97808122056952doi  a(DE-B1597)449299  a(OCoLC)794702136  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aJC571b.G525 2001eb 7aPOL0350102bisacsh04a32322100aGiving Meaning to Economic, Social, and Cultural Rights /ced. by Valerie Oosterveld, Isfahan Merali. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2011] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b3 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPennsylvania Studies in Human Rights00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. Conceptualizing Economic, Social, and Cultural Rights: Dissolving Categories -- t1. Toward the Institutional Integration of the Core Human Rights Treaties -- t2. From Division to Integration: Economic, Social, and Cultural Rights as Basic Human Rights -- t3. Defending Women’s Economic and Social Rights: Some Thoughts on Indivisibility and a New Standard of Equality -- tPart II. Current Themes: Applying Cross-Cutting Analysis -- t4. Human Rights Mean Business: Broadening the Canadian Approach to Business and Human Rights -- t5. Feminism After the State: The Rise of the Market and the Future of Women’s Rights -- t6. Advancing Safe Motherhood Through Human Rights -- t7. Canada’s New Child Support Guidelines: Do They Fulfill Canada’s International Law Obligations to Children? -- tPart III. Giving Meaning: Protection and Justiciability of Economic, Social, and Cultural Rights -- t8. Implementing Economic, Social, and Cultural Rights: The Role of National Human Rights Institutions -- t9. Bringing Economic, Social, and Cultural Rights Home: Palestinians in Occupied East Jerusalem and Israel -- t10. The Maya Petition to the Inter-American Commission on Human Rights: Indigenous Land and Resource Rights and the Conflict over Logging and Oil in Southern Belize -- tNotes -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Universal Declaration of Human Rights, arguably the founding document of the human rights movement, fully embraces economic, social, and cultural rights, as well as civil and political rights, within its text. However, for most of the fifty years since the Declaration was adopted by the General Assembly of the United Nations, the focus of the international community has been on civil and political rights. This focus has slowly shifted over the past two decades. Recent international human rights treaties—such as the Convention on the Rights of the Child and the Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination Against Women—grant equal importance to protecting and advancing nonpolitical rights.In this collection of essays, Isfahan Merali, Valerie Oosterveld, and a team of human rights scholars and activists call for the reintegration of economic, social, and cultural rights into the human rights agenda. The essays are divided into three sections. First the contributors examine traditional conceptualizations of human rights that made their categorization possible and suggest a more holistic rights framework that would dissolve such boundaries. In the second section they discuss how an integrated approach actually produces a more meaningful analysis of individual economic, social, and cultural rights. Finally, the contributors consider how these rights can be monitored and enforced, identifying ways international human rights agencies, NGOs, and states can promote them in the twenty-first century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCultural policy. 0aEco